Fix the ROB defect: make each scan all-or-nothing so a mid-scan throw consumes NO ordinal and leaves NO rows in any facet. The existing try/catch (142-232) stays; the change is WHERE state mutates.

- Restructure the per-scan body so ALL reads/builds for a scan land in PER-SCAN LOCAL staging FIRST: a local data point buffer (index/mz/intensity for this scan), a local peaks buffer, and the local Record — built BEFORE touching any streaming staging buffer, peakSpectra set, records list, scanNumberToOrdinal, or ordinal. Move the current early appends (data at 154-159, peaks at 168-176) into these locals using a placeholder; do not write the shared/streaming buffers yet.
- Keep the entire read+build (ReadMZData, OrderedPairs, the profile/centroid peak read, GetScanStatsForScanNumber, ScanTrailer, parent-derivation, BuildPrecursor) inside the try.
- ONLY after the scan fully succeeds (end of try body): assign the current ordinal to the staged rows, append them to the data/peaks streaming staging buffers (flushing a row group if at RowGroupRowCap), add peakSpectra entry if peaks exist, add the Record, set scanNumberToOrdinal[scanNumber]=ordinal, then ordinal++.
- On exception: catch → Log.Error(scan # + message) + Log.Debug(stack) + ParseInput.NewError() (NOT NewWarn — a dropped scan is data loss, matching MzMlSpectrumWriter) → continue. Because nothing was committed, ordinal is not consumed and no facet got rows. Note: the `continue` for filtered scans (level/MsLevel at 146, empty mz at 152) must also commit nothing — preserve as today.
- This preserves dense ordinals and spectra_data/spectra_peaks/metadata parity even with skips, and composes with row-group flushing (a partially-built scan never reaches a buffer). The `_precursorScanNumbers[filterKey] = scanNumber` bookkeeping (190): keep its current placement OR move it into the success-only commit — choose so a skipped scan does not poison a later child's parent lookup; document the choice in the SUMMARY (RESEARCH A1: exact S4 throw line is unconfirmed, the staging fix is correct either way).

