<risks>
- **Primary: streaming refactor regressing v1 conformance.** The move from full-facet accumulation to incremental row groups must preserve index/multiset/footer-KV invariants. Mitigation: schemas, point layout, and footer KV strings are reused verbatim; identical-multiset + parity + full-suite tests gate every change (Tasks 2,4).
- **The silent-buffer trap.** A non-seekable sink (e.g. accidentally handing the zip-entry stream to ParquetWriter) buffers the whole facet in RAM with no error — invisible RSS regression. Mitigation: OpenAsync asserts CanSeek; data facets only ever target temp FileStreams; NonSeekableSinkRejected test (Task 1); warning sign = RSS scaling with file size despite "streaming" / zero temp files on disk (Task 4 RSS measurement catches it).
- **Buffer sizing with three open facets (RESEARCH A2).** 3 × 1M-row buffers ≈ tens of MB; if too large, lower RowGroupRowCap (one-line const). Caught at Task 4 measurement.
- **Corpus availability.** MEM-02 / ROB gates depend on the large files being present; verified present today (954 MB, 418 MB, 8.4 GB). The robustness NUnit test self-ignores off-corpus so the suite stays green elsewhere.
- **Exact S4 throw line unconfirmed (RESEARCH A1).** The all-or-nothing staging is correct whether the throw is before or after the old append; optionally log the first occurrence's stack to confirm. Low risk.
</risks>

<dependencies>
- None (first phase of v2). Builds on the certified v1 writer (archived under .planning/archive/v1-point-layout/). All required APIs (Parquet.Net 5.0.1 multi-row-group, ParseInput.NewError/Errors, ZipArchive STORED, /usr/bin/time -l, mzpeak-validate) and corpus files are verified present.
